document.caption: Banjo frog — 'bonk bonk' — Also known as pobblebonks, banjo frogs sound like a banjo string being plucked, over and over. This bonking call is made by males to attract a mate, and can lead to a lovely chorus of bonks in return. Banjo frogs (Limnodynastes species) can be heard in QLD, NSW, VIC, TAS, SA and south-west WA but not in the interior or NT.

document.caption: Boobook — 'book book' or 'mo-poke' — The lovely two-note call of the boobook can be heard across Australia, including bushy urban areas. Boobooks are perch hunters: they wait on a perch then pounce on their prey, such as insects and small birds or mammals. The southern boobook (Ninox boobook) is the most common owl in Australia, whereas Tassie has its own boobook species (Ninox leucopsis).

document.caption: Fairywren — high tinkering trills — Fairywrens can be heard across most of Australia, so long as there is suitable dense vegetation for these small birds to hide in. liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The father of one of the victims of June's fatal Hunter Valley bus crash says he plans to lead a class action lawsuit over the tragedy. Ten people were killed when the bus they were travelling in rolled on the way back from a wedding reception, and another 25 were injured. AAP reports that Adam Bray, who lost his 29-year-old son Zac in the crash, has told Nine's Today show that he had been spurred to take action to improve bus safety, in particular the issue of seatbelts. Bray has flagged a class action lawsuit against the bus company, Linq Buslines, to address the broader issue of responsibility for the crash. The bus driver, Brett Button, remains before the courts facing 62 charges.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: A class action lawsuit is in the works over the fatal Hunter Valley bus crash

props.alt: Three firefighters stand on the side of a road near an overturned bus

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: In news just in, lawyers for former US president Donald Trump have proposed an April, 2026 date for the start of his criminal trial in Washington. It is one of two cases charging the former president with conspiring to overturn the results of the 2020 election. US District Judge Tanya Chutkan is expected to set the date during a court hearing scheduled for August 28.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: By North America correspondent Barbara Miller Authorities in the US state of Georgia are investigating online threats against the jurors who voted this week to indict Donald Trump and 18 others over an alleged conspiracy to overturn the 2020 presidential election results. Unlike in federal and many other state cases, the names of those jurors are listed in the indictment, which has reportedly led to doxing. In a statement, the Fulton County Sheriff’s office says it "is aware that personal information of members of the Fulton County Grand Jury is being shared on various platforms". The Sheriff’s office says the matter is being taken "very seriously" and it’s working to track down the origins of the threats. Some online posts reportedly suggested jurors were harassed, but it’s not clear whether that has actually happened. It all adds to the tension around Fulton County, Atlanta, where Trump and his co-defendants have been given until the end of next week to appear at the Rice Street jail to be booked in the case, which is expected to involve the former president having his mugshot taken.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Threats have reportedly been made against jurors who voted to indict Donald Trump in Georgia

So can the Chinese economy get out of its rut? The Business host Alicia Barry spoke to Michael Every, the global strategist for Rabobank earlier this week for his take. You can watch their full chat below:

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If you cast your mind back to 2021, you might recall SpaceX CEO Elon Musk announcing his company had acquired an undisclosed amount of Bitcoin, after Musk's other company Tesla announced it had bought $US1.5 billion worth of the cryptocurrency. At the time, Musk's endorsement of Bitcoin sent the price surging, past $US44,000. Now the Wall Street Journal is reporting that SpaceX had $US373 million worth of Bitcoin in 2021 and 2022, but has since sold it — and it's this report that has caused the cryptocurrency to drop substantially this morning. It's unclear though exactly when SpaceX might have sold its Bitcoin. (For what it's worth, neither SpaceX nor Elon Musk have commented on the report.)
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Why did Bitcoin slide? It might have something to do with Elon Musk (and SpaceX)
